data.title: See my cat! Look at it!

images.description: His name is Pico. He dies of starvation every 7.5 minutes. At least that's what he keeps on telling us. Other than that he is pretty boring.

I rent, and recently moved. The previous tenant had left furniture, the landlord told me 'trash it, keep it, whatever but probably you'll trash it because it looks crap' as its all rather old out of fashion stuff, and the landlord didn't want to pay to have it removed. Being on minimum wage and  living alone, I've had to keep it as my furniture since I'm broke and can't afford much else, and again, it'd cost me to get rid of it. Turns out, each piece is worth between 400 and 700 dollars (4 sellable things). Being a minimum pay worker, that's a lot of money for me. My partner got the frowns when I told him and sort of 'eeeeh is it yours to sell though reeeaaally' and implied it was a bit dishonest. The landlord dumped it, and left me with a house full of furniture that, had I not thankfully been poor and had none of my own, I would have had to pay to remove due to lack of space. The money I get from selling it will be to pay my rent.

Tl;dr landlord gave me furniture, told to do with as I please, turns out to be worth a bit of money.

What do, sell it without a word? Tell the landlord? As far as I'm concerned you should check what things are worth before giving them away. The landlord is not a poor landlord and has quite the empire and lavish lifestyle. This could massively benefit my poor ass.
#cat #manicure #ginger #gingercat #thatlookofbetrayal
